<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  Nearly every non-trivial app ships <strong>feature flags</strong> (gate a route/subtree on a
  runtime-evaluated flag) and <strong>experiments / A-B variant assignment</strong> (deterministically
  bucket a user, render the assigned arm, emit an exposure event), yet the
  <a href="/backlog/1414-feature-flags-experiments-declarative-gating-variant-assignm/">decision (#1414)</a>
  asks where this lands in the Web Everything constellation. The item framed three placements for
  <em>the gate</em> — a new <code>feature-flag</code> intent, vs folding it into
  <a href="/intents/access-control/">access-control</a>, vs a pure provider with no intent. But a survey of
  the upstream standard traced against the real tree <strong>reshapes the framing</strong>: the gate half
  is already standardized, and the genuinely unhomed concept is multivariate <strong>variant
  assignment</strong> and its exposure event.
</p>

<h2>Finding 1 — OpenFeature (CNCF) is the upstream standard; its typed-flag + provider shape is the convergent model</h2>
<p>
  <a href="https://openfeature.dev/specification/">OpenFeature</a> is the vendor-neutral, CNCF-Incubating
  standard for feature flagging (backed by LaunchDarkly, GitLab, Split, Dynatrace and others). Per the
  <a href="/intents/">standards-bodies-are-upstream</a> principle, WE aligns to it and borrows its
  vocabulary rather than re-inventing. Its shape:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Resolution structure</strong> — a flag evaluation returns
    <code>{ value, variant, reason, errorCode }</code>. <code>variant</code> names which arm was returned;
    <code>reason</code> is a <em>standardized enum</em>:
    <code>STATIC · DEFAULT · TARGETING_MATCH · SPLIT · CACHED · DISABLED · UNKNOWN · STALE · ERROR</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Typed flags</strong> — boolean / string / number / object. The <em>boolean</em> case is the
    binary gate; the <em>string / object</em> case is the multivariate variant selector. This typed split
    is the load-bearing distinction below.</li>
  <li><strong>Provider</strong> — a swappable implementation resolving values from a source of truth,
    registered in a global singleton (init/evaluate/shutdown, bindable per logical domain). The running app
    <strong>consults</strong> it on every evaluation — a genuine runtime-DI seam (cf.
    <a href="/backlog/052-jsx-rendering-strategy-axis/">#052</a>/<a href="/backlog/081-module-as-a-service-provider/">#081</a>),
    and the only lock (the impl stays escapable).</li>
  <li><strong>Evaluation context</strong> — arbitrary contextual data (user id, locale) is the targeting
    basis, mirroring the predicate-context the Guard provider already takes.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Finding 2 — the gate half is ALREADY standardized in WE; only variant assignment is unhomed</h2>
<p>
  <a href="/intents/access-control/">Access Control</a> already declares
  <code>feature-flag</code> as a first-class <strong>authority kind</strong>
  (<code>src/_data/intents/access-control.json:24-30</code>) on the
  <a href="/projects/webguards/">Guard</a> provider seam
  (<code>src/_data/projects/webguards.json:4</code>) — <em>"feature-flag = temporary entitlement/rollout
  (same provider seam, materially different stakes)."</em> It carries the deny-outcome family
  (<code>hide | redirect | forbid | cloak</code>) and a server-authoritative trust boundary. So the
  <strong>binary gate is done</strong>: both "a new feature-flag intent for the gate" and "fold the gate
  into access-control" dissolve — the latter is already the shipped answer. What access-control's
  <em>allow/deny</em> gate <strong>cannot</strong> express is a flag that resolves to <em>one of N
  variants</em>. That multivariate selector — plus its exposure event — is the genuinely unhomed concept,
  and the real subject of the decision.
</p>

<h2>Finding 3 — OpenFeature splits Tracking from Evaluation; the exposure event is a telemetry compose</h2>
<p>
  OpenFeature's <a href="https://openfeature.dev/specification/sections/tracking/">Tracking API</a> is a
  <strong>separate spec section</strong> from evaluation: the <em>exposure</em> ("which arm they saw")
  comes from the evaluation, the <em>conversion</em> ("what they did") from a
  <code>track(eventName, context, details)</code> call. This is the upstream's own ratification of the
  flag&harr;telemetry seam: the exposure is an <strong>emit-to-a-sink compose</strong>, not new gate
  machinery. WE routes it through the telemetry sink prepared in
  <a href="/backlog/1415-telemetry-analytics-events-declarative-event-emission-vocabu/">#1415</a> — the
  variant intent <em>declares</em> the exposure, telemetry <em>delivers</em> it (a named seam, not a merge
  of the two items).
</p>

<h2>Finding 4 — incumbents converge; deterministic bucketing is impl behind the provider, never UX</h2>
<p>
  The provider models converge: LaunchDarkly treats flag variations as experiment arms and sends a
  <em>feature-event</em> exposure on evaluation; Statsig's evaluation is deterministic
  (<code>SHA256(salt + unit) % 10000</code>); Unleash stacks activation strategies; GrowthBook's Safe
  Rollout ramps on the same statistical engine as experiments; Flagsmith adds multivariate testing.
  Crucially, <strong>deterministic bucketing is an implementation detail behind the provider</strong> — a
  hash of a salt and a unit id. Per <a href="/intents/">intents-are-UX-only</a> and
  <a href="/backlog/020-base-select-as-customrenderer/">Impl-Is-Not-A-Standard</a>, it is never a UX value
  and never a WE artifact beyond the provider contract.
</p>

<h2>Classification (per-element pass)</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Binary gate</strong> — Intent, already shipped as <code>authority: feature-flag</code> on
    access-control / the Guard provider; runtime-DI; most-permissive default. <em>Settled — no fork.</em></li>
  <li><strong>Variant assignment</strong> — Intent layer; a dimension (N arms are all legitimate
    simultaneous end-states); expose the whole axis; DI-injectable (consults an evaluation provider);
    most-permissive default = the control/default arm (mirrors OpenFeature <code>DEFAULT</code>); seam =
    variant&rarr;provider and variant&rarr;telemetry.</li>
  <li><strong>Exposure event</strong> — a telemetry emit-to-a-sink; composes with #1415; default no-op
    sink. <em>Supported by default + a named seam, not a fork.</em></li>
  <li><strong>Deterministic bucketing</strong> — impl behind the provider; excluded from UX. <em>Supported
    by default.</em></li>
</ul>

<h2>The prepared forks</h2>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 1 — Home for variant assignment.</strong> A separate <code>experiment</code> intent
    <em>(recommended)</em> vs a third <code>surface</code> on access-control vs no-intent. No-intent is the
    <strong>broken</strong> branch (render-the-assigned-arm is a UX declaration an author needs to write
    against — a bare provider gives nothing to declare); and the access-control deny-outcome family
    (allow/deny) cannot carry a pick-one-of-N resolution.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 2 — Provider identity.</strong> A distinct evaluation provider reusing the Guard seam
    <em>pattern</em> <em>(recommended)</em> vs the same Guard provider instance. A variant arm is
    <strong>not</strong> a security verdict; routing both through one provider risks a client-side gate
    masquerading as authorization, breaking access-control's server-authoritative trust boundary.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 3 — Exposure event routing.</strong> Routed through #1415's telemetry sink
    <em>(recommended)</em> vs its own event family. OpenFeature's separate Tracking API is the upstream
    precedent for the compose.
  </li>
</ul>

